Cell.Data: The cover page must be in A4 size and it does not contain a page number.
No bold or centred text is allowed, except for the Cancels & Replaces box

Must be present on the cover page: Cote and cote suffix. All documents, whatever their classification, must have a cote number; this is placed at the top right of the cover page, in the fixed zone which has been determined for this purpose.
Must be present on the cover page: language classification. It specified on the cover page has to match that used in the document
Must be present on the cover page: Document Classification (Confidential, Official Use or Unclassified).
Must be present on the cover page: JT Number. A unigue reference (JT number) generated by the SRP system is inserted on the bottom left corner of the cover page during the submission process.

Must be present on the cover page: OLIS Date. The current date, generated by the SRP system is inserted on the top right corner of the cover page (beneath the document cote) during the submission processas upon submitting the document to the documents desk.
Must be present on the cover page: Title
Must be present on the cover page: The standard disclaimer is inserted at the bottom of the cover page, as well as the mention whether to document is complete on OLIS in its' original format
Optionally present on the cover page: document contact.
The cote root has to be created in the Cote Management Database which is linked to the "Bodies book"
When a /final document exists, the cote cannot be used anymore, except for corrigendum or addendum
The document cote must appear on every page. This cote has to correspond to the cote used on the cover page

The document cote must be positioned appropriately in respect to its document classification. The code number should appear at the top left of even-numbered pages, and at the top right of oddnumbered pages; if this is not possible, and in the case of all confidential documents, the code number should appear at the top right of every page, flush against the margin.
The document cote cannot contain roman numerals
The document cote cannot contain non-standard suffixes
A valid cote must be used throughout the document e.g. if users are authoring separate components, then the merge of these must result in the same cote throughout
The font face of the document cote must not be altered
A document code number should never be split
All documents need a classification (i.e. Confidential, Official Use or Unclassified).

Confidential documents must use the “Confidential” classification and “Draft” documents must replace their prefix with “PROV”. The suffix "PROV" is used for provisional documents( for example C(2012)14/PROV)

In the case of confidential documents, the word "CONFIDENTIAL" should appear (once) on the cover page, and then at the top left of all successive pages, on the same line as the code number. The word "confidential" must appear on the top left corner and the cote must be on the same line on the top right corner
All committee documents, including annexes unless they are physically attached to the main document, must start with a standard cover page.
The text itself should start (for example with the table of contents, if one is included) on the second page, which is numbered 2.
Watermarks to denote Classification (i.e. “Draft” or “Confidential”) are not allowed in documents. When a document is manually declassified a watermark is inserted on the cover page only.
Page numbers must be present on all pages, except the Cover Page
The standard paper size is A4
Page breaks should be used correctly in order to avoid grouped content (i.e. a list or a corresponding table) from being orphaned.
The language classification specified on the cover page has to match that used in the document
Whatever the language of the document is, it is essential that the title must be in one of the official languages (English or French).
For documents translated into a third language, it must be checked if the document already exists on OLIS in one of the two official languages of the OECD.
Words that have been changed should be underlined or otherwise highlighted. Completely new paragraphs should be sidelined throughout their length.
Crosses should be placed where words have been removed
Where whole sentences have been deleted, double square brackets [] should be used
If a sentence has been moved, its original position should be indicated and an arrow drawn to its new position.

Track changes must be removed except in those cases where a document is a revision. A revised document must have a cote ending in „/REV‟. A document with either the prefix /RD or /WD in the cote may also have track changes
When referring to a different document, you must include a link.
Agenda type document must contain a link to an event registered in the Event Management System (EMS).
If a table has been taken from another publication, the text or the notes should contain explanatory information in the Sources
Precise references should be supplied for source material.
If earlier OECD documents have been drawn upon, the necessary references should again be supplied.

For official documents numbering must be applied to paragraphs and changes need to be tracked in the XML because paragraph numbers are used at committee for review. A former paragraph maybe be replaced with a new one but the old number needs to be retained as a record. Today this is done manually by putting the old paragraph number in square brackets next to the new number.
Application but not all paragraphs have to be numbered
Paragraph numbering can be sequential throughout the document (1,2,3) or by chapter (1.1, 1.2, 2.1, 2.2)
Sections of a documents, as well as tables, figures and boxes, are also numbered and following the sequential or chapter based model used.
Numbering of lists is maintained at 5 levels, except in boxes where there are only 3 levels.
When the document is converted to a CRC Publication the paragraph numbers are removed but the chapter numbering (and numbering of components are retained).
Acronyms and abbreviations, unless in general use (OECD, UNESCO, GDP, etc.), should be spelled out the first time they are used in a text.
To be checked against exiting typographical rules
When translations of official titles or names are used in the text, they should also be given in full in the original language to avoid retranslation.
To be checked against exiting typographical rules
Expressions whose meaning is not apparent except in specialised circles should be clearly explained.
To be checked against exiting typographical rules
The agenda appears on the reverse side of the standard cover page.
The agenda item number appears flush against the margin, followed by a full stop, and the text is indented at the first TAB.
Document reference numbers, where provided, should appear flush against the right margin.
One blank line should be left between agenda items
The name and country of the chairman should be centred, bolded, and followed by three blank lines.
The country names appear in alphabetical order, at the left margin, in capitals and bolded.
The names of participants appear at the next TAB, in capitals, and should be listed alphabetically by rank.
The name of the institution represented should be indicated at the final TAB; it is not necessary to include the address.
A blank line should be left between each country list.

ss:Data.Font: Secretariat participants should be listed alphabetically by rank, at the end, under a centred, bolded heading

Cell.Data: the name of the committee and the place, date and time of meeting must always appear on the cover page;
a list of participants must start on page 2 of minutes and summary records, or as an annex in the case of reports;
a table of contents listing the agenda items should appear immediately after the list of participants;

ss:Data.Font: the text of the minutes or summary record appears next and should usually start on a new page, but if there is sufficient space the text of the minutes may start on the same page as the list of agenda items, in which case three blank lines should be left before starting the text;

Cell.Data: within the text, delegates are referred to not by name, but as the Delegate of the participating country, e.g. "the Delegate for Norway";
agreements, decisions adopted and items noted by the committee appear at the end.
Maximum file sizes of output documents (.DocX, PDF, XML to be enforced)

Publication content should not be less than 80 A4-equivalent pages and not exceed 600 A4-equivalent pages. If these conditions are not met, an alert should be issued within the Publication drafting phase
Chapter length should not vary beyond a 50% difference. If these conditions are not met, an alert should be issued within the Publication drafting phase.

Components in publications belong to Frontmatter, Body or Backmatter. Even though not always visible in the final publication output, these distinctions are necessary to establish a certain number of editorial rules.
Frontmatter components are: Foreword, Acknowledgements, Abbreviations and acronyms, Editorial, Preface, Executive Summary
Body components are: Chapters/articles i. Parts are groupings of chapters. They do not contain content, only components. ii. Any introduction or conclusion chapters must have descriptive titles.
TOCs must be displayed in final outputs and are calculated from the components
The following publication components are mandatory: - If periodical publication: articles - If non periodical publication: Foreword, chapters.
The following components are not mandatory: Abbreviations/Acronyms, Preface, Editorial, Executive Summary, Annexes, Glossary.

Annexes can be embedded in chapters or are elements of the full publication. Authors must be able to express clearly, by whatever means, if an annex belongs to the whole publication, to a part or to a chapter. (Note that “Appendices” should be labelled as “Annexes”.)

Bibliographies and references are embedded at chapter/article level. Exceptionally, they can become a stand-alone component at the end of the publication if the publication is broken up into components

There are three types of citations: o references: list of documentation cited in the content. o bibliography: list of documentation cited in the content and documentation used to produce the content. o further reading: recommended list of additional references that the user can consult for further research/information on the publication subject.
Publicaion PDF rendering starts on page 3.
There are no blank odd (right-hand) pages, or pages with only one or two lines.
Notes are grouped by chapter, not at the end of the publication.
Chapter abstract is mandatory metadata: maximum 150 words (English) and 170 (French). This is noted in the OECDAuthorMetaProcess XLS
p. 25 of FSD listed as optional metadata
A part should not contain a preface or a foreword
p. 26 of FSD. Allowed in Narrdoc.
Executive summary does not contain definition list, equation, chemical structure, graphic, figure, table, embedded content, external content reference
p. 30 of FSD, allowed in Narrdoc.
A foreword does not contain equation, chemical structure, graphic, figure, table, embedded content, external content reference.
p. 30 of FSD, allowed in Narrdoc.
A preface does not contain equation, chemical structure, graphic, figure, table, external content reference. A preface can contain a signature.
p. 31 of FSD, allowed in Narrdoc.

Tables may be labelled in one of two ways: from 1 to n throughout a document; or, if a text comprises several chapters, the table numbers may follow their chapter numbers, i.e. the first table in Chapter 1 would be called "Table 1.1", the first table in Chapter 2 would be "Table 2.1", and so on.
Table Titles: type on the same line, and centre, the word "Table" and its number, full stop, two spaces and then the title with the initial letter capitalised.
If a table is to appear within text, leave two blank lines before and after the table
If a table has to be continued overleaf, the titles of columns should appear on that page also, and the word "continued" typed at the top left margin
Where decimals are used, the decimal point is represented by a full stop (period) in both English and French
To be checked against exiting typographical rules
Never use a small letter "1" to represent the figure "1", nor a capital "O" to represent zero
To be checked against exiting typographical rules
When paginating a table which is presented in landscape format, the number should appear at the same point as on a page of text
In tables, millions are typed thus: 200{hard space}000{hard space}000
To be checked against exiting typographical rules
A single hyphen is used to indicate negative numbers, e.g. -35 500, -3.4, -3%.
To be checked against exiting typographical rules
Fractions may be typed as in either 3'Afhard space}per cent or 3 {hard space} 1/2 {hard space }per cent
To be checked against exiting typographical rules
Explanatory notes. Leave two blank lines after the table before typing, in italics and flush against the left margin, Note: (or Notes:).

Source(s). When a source is quoted, this should appear after the reference notes. Leave one blank line after the last note before typing the word Source: (followed by a colon and in italics) flush against the left margin. Details of sources should be indented at the second TAB
Tables, no matter how small, should not appear in notes

Il n’est plus nécessaire d’inscrire « http:// » dans les URLs lorsque l’adresse est de type « www.toto.com ». Cette mention reste indispensable si l’adresse ne comporte pas de « www » comme dans « http://adresse.toto.com ». Si l’URL termine une phrase, elle est immédiatement suivie par un point « www.toto.com. ».
Word reconnait automatiquement les adresses E-mail et les surligne en bleu. Il n’est pas nécessaire de les composer en italique.

On écrit « et » sauf s’il s’agit d’un sigle, auquel cas on conserve « & ».

On place des crochets à l’intérieur des parenthèses: « (texte[texte] texte) ». Toutefois, si les parenthèses ou les crochets encadrent des chiffres ou des références, respecter l’interprétation de l’auteur

ss:Data.Font: Dans le cas de citations à deux niveaux, la citation interne est placée entre des guillemets anglais doubles : «
Dans le cas de citations à trois niveaux, les citations internes sont placée entre des guillemets anglais doubles pour la première et simples pour la seconde : «

Cell.Data: Les listes doivent toutes suivre la même structure. Phrase complète : majuscule en début de phrase + point final à la fin de chaque élément de l’énumération. Phrase incomplète ou liste : pas de majuscule, pas de ponctuation, point final au dernier élément uniquement. Voir p. 34 du nouveau Style Guide.
Les appels de notes doivent être placés après la ponctuation et sont de préférence placées à la fin de la phrase. Voir p. 28 du nouveau Style Guide.
